{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583136"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:08:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:08:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2082"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2082"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.43,0,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2082"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77632"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2082"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2082"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63145"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3711"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"220"},{"type":"contributions","id":"729"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26676"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77632"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents with easy bruising and prolonged bleeding after dental procedures. She reports heavy menstrual periods since menarche. Her parent and sister have similar symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory results:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003Evon Willebrand factor antigen: 45 IU/dL (50-160)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Evon Willebrand factor activity: 15 IU/dL (50-160)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFactor VIII: 65 IU/dL (50-150)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelet count: 250 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type 1 von Willebrand disease","Type 2 von Willebrand disease","Mild haemophilia B","Platelet function defect","Mild haemophilia A"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Etype 2 von Willebrand disease\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by disproportionately reduced von Willebrand factor activity (15 IU/dL) compared to antigen levels (45 IU/dL), giving an activity:antigen ratio of 0.33. The family history and mucocutaneous bleeding symptoms are typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect diagnoses can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 1 von Willebrand disease\u003C/strong\u003E - Shows proportional reduction in both activity and antigen levels, unlike this case\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMild haemophilia B\u003C/strong\u003E - Would show isolated reduction in factor IX with normal von Willebrand factor levels\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet function defect\u003C/strong\u003E - Would show normal von Willebrand factor levels with abnormal platelet function tests\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMild haemophilia A\u003C/strong\u003E - Would show isolated reduction in factor VIII with normal von Willebrand factor levels\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of a positive family history, mucocutaneous bleeding symptoms, and laboratory evidence of disproportionately reduced von Willebrand factor activity confirms type 2 von Willebrand disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Type 2 von Willebrand disease is characterised by disproportionately reduced von Willebrand factor activity compared to antigen levels.","Family history and mucocutaneous bleeding symptoms are typical presentations of von Willebrand disease.","Laboratory diagnosis of type 2 von Willebrand disease shows activity:antigen ratio less than 0.7."],"references":["Baronciani L, Peyvandi F. How to make an accurate diagnosis of von Willebrand disease. Thrombosis Research. 2019;3848(19)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63145"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2082"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63145"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:45:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:46:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2082"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77632"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m